The Federal Government has urged Nigerians, especially youths to avoid risky behaviours that make them vulnerable to contracting HIV, even as they express love to their loved ones on Valentine’s Day. It noted that persons between the ages of 15 to 24 years constitute the highest number of new HIV infections across the country. Hence, it urged Nigerians to ensure that they know their HIV status.   ‘Nigeria needs legislation compelling banks to contact…     The Nation’s Ololade makes final shortlist for Fetisov…     CJN throws open Supreme Court Justice job to lawyers   The Director General of the National Agency for the Control of AIDS (NACA), Dr. Gambo Aliyu, who made this known in a statement by the Head of Public Relations and Protocols of the Agency, Toyin Aderibigbe, urged Nigerians to remain faithful in their relationships, and for those who cannot abstain from s3x to practice safer s3x. The NACA boss said: “New HIV infection is currently highest among young people aged 15-24 years. It is important to reduce this worrying trend among Nigerian youths by encouraging faithful relationships for those who cannot abstain from s3x to practice safer s3x. “This period is particularly noted for young people expressing their love for one another. Nigerians, especially the youths, should express love within the context of caring deeply for their loved ones and avoid behaviour that will make them vulnerable to HIV/AIDS .”As we express love on this day, remember to love wisely. As members of the wider society, your health and productivity is vital to the future of our country. So, I urge you to avoid risky behaviors as we commemorate Valentine’s Day. Love wisely, share love not HIV. Get a HIV test today.” SPONSORED